22|title=Colonel Tatham and Other Virginia Engineers|journal=William and Mary Quarterly|series=Second Series|volume=II|issue=2|pages=81\u201384|doi=10.2307/1921435 |doi-access=free|jstor=<!-- Deny Citation Bot-->|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=On\u00eds|first=Jos\u00e9 de|date=1952|title=The United States as Seen by Spanish American Writers (1776\u20131890)|location=New York|publisher=Hispanic Institute in the United States|hdl=2027/uc1.b3626361|hdl-access=free|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Randall|first=Stephen J.|date=1992|title=Colombia and the United States: Hegemony and Interdependence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FWiHAInapZQC&pg=PP1|location=Athens|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=<!-- Deny Citation Bot-->|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Robertson|first=William Spence|date=September 1915|title=The First Legations of the United States in Latin America|journal=Mississippi Valley Historical Review|volume=2|issue=2|pages=183\u2013212|doi=10.2307/1887061|jstor=1887061|jstor-access=free|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Vilar|first=Mar|date=2001|title=Un gram\u00e1tico anglista poco conocido: Manuel Torres, adaptador en 1811 en los Estados Unidos para la ense\u00f1anza del espa\u00f1ol a angl\u00f3fonos del m\u00e9todo 'Nature Displayed' de N.G. Dufief y colaborador de los ling\u00fcistas y lexic\u00f3grafos Hargous y Vel\u00e1zquez de la Cadena|url=https://dialnet.unirioja.es/descarga/articulo/260151.pdf|journal=ES: Revista de Filolog\u00eda Inglesa|language=es|volume=23|pages=241\u2013252|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book <!-- Deny Citation Bot-->|last=Vogeley|first=Nancy|date=2011|title=The Bookrunner: A History of Inter-American Relations\u2014Print, Politics, and Commerce in the United States and Mexico, 1800\u20131830|location=Philadelphia|publisher=American Philosophical Society|jstor=41507683|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Whitaker|first=Arthur P.|date=1954|title=The Western Hemisphere Idea: Its Rise and Decline|url=https://archive.org/details/westernhemispher00whit|location=Ithaca, New York|publisher=Cornell University Press|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Warren|first=Richard A.|date=October 2004|title=Displaced 'Pan-Americans' and the Transformation of the Catholic Church of Philadelphia, 1789\u20131850|url=https://journals.psu.edu/pmhb/article/view/45724/45445|journal=Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography|volume=128|issue=4|pages=343\u2013366|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Torres, Manuel (diplomat)}}\n[[Category:1762 births]]\n[[Category:1822 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Colombia to the United States]]\n[[Category:Colombian writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:People of the Spanish American wars of independence]]\n[[Category:American people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Spanish emigrants to Colombia]]\n[[Category:Colombian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLatino(link changed toHispanic and Latino Americans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manuel_Torres_(diplomat)"}
{"title_page": "Miss Bala (2019 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 film directed by Catherine Hardwicke}}\n{{for|2019 Indian drama film|Bala (2019 film)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Miss Bala\n| image          = Miss Bala poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Catherine Hardwicke]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Pablo Cruz\n* [[Kevin Misher]]\n}}\n| writer         = Gareth Dunnett-Alcocer\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Miss Bala (2011 film)|Miss Bala]]''|Gerardo Naranjo<br>Mauricio Katz}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gina Rodriguez]]\n* [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]]\n* [[Anthony Mackie]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Alex Heffes]]\n| cinematography = Patrick Murguia\n| editing        = Terilyn A. Shropshire\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]\n* [[Canana Films]]\n* Misher Films\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|2|1|United States}}\n| runtime        = 104 minutes\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* Mexico\n}}\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* Spanish\n}}\n| budget         = $15 million<ref name=BOM/>\n| gross          = $15.4 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=missbala.htm|title=Miss Bala (2019)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=July 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NUM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Miss-Bala-(Remake)-(2019)#tab=summary|title=Miss Bala (2019)|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n'''''Miss Bala''''' (English: \"Miss Bullet\") is a 2019 [[action film|action]] [[thriller film|thriller]] film directed by [[Catherine Hardwicke]] and written by Gareth Dunnet-Alcocer, based on the [[Miss Bala (2011 film)|2011 Mexican film of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/catherine-hardwicke-miss-bala-remake-gina-rodriguez-courted-1202061089/|title=Catherine Hardwicke To Helm \u2018Miss Bala\u2019 Remake; Gina Rodriguez Courted|last=Fleming Jr|first=Mike|date=April 4, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref> The film stars [[Gina Rodriguez]], [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]], and [[Anthony Mackie]], and follows a woman who trains to take down a Mexican drug cartel after her friend is kidnapped.\n\nThe film was released in the United States on February 1, 2019, by [[Columbia Pictures]], in [[Dolby Cinema]], and grossed over $15 million on a $15 million budget making it an average grosser. While Rodriguez's performance received some praise, critics compared the film unfavorably to the original, saying it suffered from \"bland action and predictable story beats\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/miss-bala-is-a-rocky-remake/|title=Miss Bala Is A Rocky Remake|author=Ryan Fujitani|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plot== \nGloria Fuentes is a [[Latin-American]] [[makeup artist]] from [[Los Angeles]] who goes on a trip to visit her best friend Suzu in [[Tijuana, Mexico]].\n\nWhen the pair go to a local night club, Suzu plans to impress the Mexican Chief of Police, Saucedo, in order to help her chances in the Miss Baja  California beauty pageant which she has entered. When Gloria goes to the bathroom, armed gunmen break in through the vents and attempt to kidnap Gloria out of her stall but ultimately give her time to escape while they attack the club. Chaos ensues as Gloria is separated from Suzu. The next morning, Gloria is unable to get in contact with Suzu and decides to ride with a police officer to try to find Suzu. She informs the police officer that she has information on the men who attacked the club, and the officer asks her to follow him to the station. When the officer takes a break in a remote location, Gloria is taken by members of the Los Estrellas gang, the same men who shot up the club.\n\nThe gang take her to their headquarters, where Lino, the gang leader, agrees to help her find Suzu if she agrees to work for them. Gloria is reluctant but eventually agrees as she does not have much choice, and is told to get into a car and park it on a corner of a building. Gloria does the job, and when she leaves the car and joins the men at the top of a hill overlooking the building, they blow up the building, revealed to be a DEA safehouse containing three agents.\n\nLino then sends Gloria to the Miss Baja pageant, where she attempts an escape through the bathroom. Gloria escapes and encounters a DEA agent, Brian Reich, who takes her into custody and eventually lets her go but not before he puts a tracking device on her since the DEA are aiming to monitor Los Estrellas.\n\nGloria returns to Suzu's apartment and finds Lino there, and is sent to San Diego with blood money and drugs attached to her car. Upon crossing the border Gloria is given an arsenal of guns to bring back to Mexico by a gangster named Jimmy, and then told to meet in a large parking lot. Gloria then informs Brian about the meet-up at the parking lot, where he promises to send a SWAT team to rescue her during the mission to capture Lino and the Los Estrellas gang. As Gloria arrives at the parking lot, the men in Los Estrellas get their weapons. However the police show up under Brian's command, causing a gunfight to ensue in the lot. Gloria escapes to a nearby gate where Brian promised to send the SWAT team to pick her up, but sees nobody there. Gloria realizes that Brian had no intention to help her, only to capture Los Estrellas. Seeing Gloria stranded in the middle of the gunfight, Lino runs to Gloria to save her, but is shot in the leg. After a moment of hesitation, Gloria decides to help Lino and together, they escape with the other members of Los Estrellas.\n\nThe gang head to another safe house, where Gloria meets a woman named Isabella. Isabella herself was threatened into joining Los Estrellas, and bears an infigurative tattoo, meaning she belongs to them. When Gloria hears that they will be checking phones to find a mole in the group, she transfers the chip that Brian gave her to another phone. Lino brings Gloria on a ride to meet some family, and they spend time together as Lino shares his dream of living a simple life in the countryside despite his involvement in a gang. As they return to the safe house, the gang informs Lino that they have found the mole. Unknowingly and to her dismay, Gloria had put the chip in the phone belonging to Isabella, who is killed by Lino for being the suspected mole. Gloria is extremely upset, and the next morning she lashes out at Lino.\n\nLino explains his plan to kill The Mexican Chief of Police, Saucedo, to Gloria, and shows her a video of Suzu being auctioned off to various buyers. He explains that Suzu was taken the night of the club shooting, and is sold as an escort every night. His plan is to send Gloria to the Miss Baja pageant and ensure her victory by bribing the judges, afterwhich she will be invited to the afterparty organized by Saucedo. Gloria participates in the pageant and wins, and is then invited to the afterparty at Saucedo's beach home. At the party, she agrees to meet with Saucedo in one of the villas, which she informs Lino of the whereabouts via an in-ear microphone. Before meeting Saucedo, Gloria sees Suzu, and they reunite, Gloria telling Suzu that everything will be okay. However, when Suzu shows her a tattoo on her hand, the same tattoo that Isabella had, Gloria quickly realizes that Lino deceived her and that he had known where Suzu was the whole time.\n\nAs Gloria follows Saucedo into the villa, she writes on a postcard that Lino is going to kill him. Saucedo quickly escapes outside just as Los Estrellas begin their attack, and Gloria goes to find Suzu armed with a gun from one of the fallen Los Estrellas gang members. As Gloria goes to find Suzu, she is forced to shoot Saucedo in the leg after he tries to hold Suzu hostage, but then Lino kills him and thanks Gloria for her help in killing Saucedo. Gloria points her gun at Lino, confessing she knows that he was aware of Suzu's whereabouts. Lino tries to bargain with Gloria telling her that they both did what needed to be done, but she ends up shooting and killing him.\n\nThe two women are soon arrested when the cops arrive at the party, and when Gloria is taken into an interrogation room, she finds Jimmy, the man she had received the weapons from in San Diego, and realizes that he is a CIA agent. Gloria has Jimmy free Suzu and herself, and she returns Suzu to her family and goes back into the car with Jimmy, driving off to join the CIA.\n\n==Cast== \n* [[Gina Rodriguez]] as Gloria Fuentes, a [[makeup artist]] from [[Los Angeles]].\n* [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]] as Lino Esparza, the chief of Las Estrellas, a gang from [[Tijuana, Mexico|Tijuana]].\n* [[Matt Lauria]] as Brian Reich, a [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] officer.\n* [[Ricardo Abarca]] as Pollo, Lino's main henchman.\n* Cristina Rodlo as Suzu Ram\u00f3s, Gloria's best friend who lives in [[Tijuana, Mexico|Tijuana]] and a competitor on the Miss Baja California pageant.\n* Sebasti\u00e1n Cano as Chava Ram\u00f3s, Suzu's little brother who lives with her.\n* [[Dami\u00e1n Alc\u00e1zar]] as Rafael Saucedo, [[Tijuana, Mexico|Tijuana]] chief of police.\n* [[Anthony Mackie]] as Jimmy, a gangster from [[San Diego]], who is secretly a [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agent.\n* [[Aislinn Derbez]] as Isabel, a woman abducted by Las Estrellas.\n* Lilian Guadalupe Tapia Robles as Do\u00f1a Rosita, a woman who work for Las Estrellas.\n* Erick Rene Delgadillo Urbina as Tuc\u00e1n, Lino's henchman.\n* Mikhail Plata as Chivo, Lino's henchman.\n* Jorge Humberto Millan Mardue\u00f1o as Ortiz, Lino's henchman.\n* [[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]] as Justin, Gloria's boss in [[Los Angeles]].\n* Jos\u00e9 Sefami as Don Ramon, a man who work for Rafael Saucedo.\n* Gaby Orihuela as the coordinator of the Miss Baja California pageant.\n* Roberto Sosa as the police officer who secretly work for Las Estrellas.\n\n==Production==\nIn April 2017, it was announced [[Catherine Hardwicke]] would direct the film, from a screenplay by Gareth Dunnet-Alcocer, with [[Kevin Misher]] and Pablo Cruz producing the film, with [[Andy Berman]] serving as an executive producer on the film. In May 2017, [[Gina Rodriguez]] and [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/gina-rodriguez-ismael-cruz-cordova-miss-bala-sony-1202092067/|title=Gina Rodriguez Set To Star In \u2018Miss Bala\u2019, Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova Cast As Male Lead|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=May 15, 2017|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref> In July 2017, [[Matt Lauria]], Cristina Rodlo, and [[Aislinn Derbez]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/matt-lauria-cristina-rodlo-gina-rodriguez-in-miss-bala-remake-1202500248/|title=Matt Lauria and Cristina Rodlo Join Gina Rodriguez in \u2018Miss Bala\u2019 Remake (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=July 19, 2017|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BWi_ZUggtFR/|title=Hot set with these crazy people @hereisgina @ismaelcruzcordova @richieabarca #moviemaking \ud83d\ude0d\ud83c\udfac\ud83c\udfa5|website=[[Instagram]]|first=Aislinn|last=Derbez|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref> [[Anthony Mackie]] later joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/miss-bala-animated-spider-man-show-sonys-commitment-to-diverse-heroes-1202784274/|title=\u2018Miss Bala,\u2019 Animated Spider-Man Show Sony\u2019s Commitment to Diverse Heroes|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=April 23, 2018|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref> The cast and crew are said to be 95 percent [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cinemacon-sony-touts-diversity-upcoming-movies-1105236|title=CinemaCon: Sony Touts Diversity of Its Upcoming Movies|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Lopez 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/miss-bala-gina-rodriguez-1203029195/|title=Gina Rodriguez\u2019s \u2018Miss Bala\u2019 Features Rare Leading Role for Latinx Actor, Diverse Crew|last=Lopez|first=Ricardo|date=2018-11-16|work=Variety|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en-US}}</ref> Sony reportedly spent $15 million producing the film.<ref name=\"Lopez 2018\" />\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released in the United States on February 1, 2019, after having previously been set for a January 25, 2019 release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/sony-dates-trio-for-2019-miss-bala-a-dogs-way-home-the-crow-1202308464/|title=Sony Dates Trio For 2019: \u2018Miss Bala\u2019, \u2018A Dog\u2019s Way Home\u2019 & \u2018The Crow\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=March 2, 2018|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/escape-room-miss-bala-release-date-sony-gina-rodriguez-tyler-labine-1202482018/|title=Sony Moves \u2018Escape Room\u2019 Up By A Month & \u2018Miss Bala\u2019 By A Week|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Erik|last=Pederson|date=October 12, 2018|accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref> It was in the United Kingdom on February 8, 2019.<ref name=\"Filmoria\">{{cite web|url=https://www.filmoria.co.uk/presenting-the-first-trailer-poster-and-images-for-miss-bala/|title=Miss Bala - The First Trailer, Poster and Images|publisher=Filmoria.co.uk |access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Miss Bala'' has grossed $15 million in the United States and Canada, and $173,237 in other territories, for a worldwide gross of $15.2 million, against a production budget of $15 million.<ref name=BOM/><ref name=NUM/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Miss Bala'' was projected to gross $6\u20139 million from 2,203 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=preview>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-box-office-miss-bala-glass-20190130-story.html|title=Can Gina Rodriguez's action movie 'Miss Bala' unseat 'Glass' at the box office?|work=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |date=January 30, 2019 |first=Ryan |last=Faughnder|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> It made $2.8 million on its first day, including $650,000 from Thursday night previews. It went on to debut to $6.7 million, finishing third at the box office. ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' wrote that given its $15 million production budget, an opening of $10\u201312 million would've been an ideal start in order for the film to turn a profit.<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/miss-bala-fires-up-650k-in-previews-before-heading-into-slow-super-bowl-weekend-1202547407/|title=\u2018Glass\u2019 Still Has Class With Third Weekend Win; \u2018Miss Bala\u2019 Fires Blanks In Lowest Super Bowl Frame In 19 Years \u2013 Sunday Final|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 3, 2018|first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> It fell 60% in its second weekend to $2.7 million, finishing 10th.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/lego-movie-2-chris-pratt-what-men-want-cold-pursuit-liam-neeson-box-office-weekend-1202552562/|title=\u2018Lego Movie 2\u2019 Comes Apart With $34M+ Opening; \u2018What Men Want\u2019 Solid With $18M+ In Another Blas\u00e9 B.O. Weekend|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 10, 2018|first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 22% based on 105 reviews, with an average rating of 4.59/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Miss Bala'' suggests Gina Rodriguez has a future as an action hero; unfortunately, it also demonstrates how hard it is to balance set pieces against a compelling story.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/miss_bala_2019|title=Miss Bala (2019)|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[weighted average]] score of 41 out of 100, based on 30 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/miss-bala-2019|title=Miss Bala reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 3.5 out of 5 stars; social media monitor RelishMix noted online responses to the film were \"mixed-to-negative\".<ref name=opening/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemascore.com|title=Find CinemaScore|format=Type \"Miss Bala\" in the search box|publisher=[[CinemaScore]]|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Roeper]], writing for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' was critical of the film, saying, \"Run away from Gina Rodriguez's ludicrous drug running shoot-em-up... ''Miss Bala'' is an early contender for a spot on my list of the worst movies of 2019.\"<ref name=opening/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDB title|5941692}}\n* {{Mojo title|missbala}}\n\n{{Catherine Hardwicke}}\n\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American crime drama films]]\n[[Category:Mexican films]]\n[[Category:Mexican action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Mexican crime drama films]]\n[[Category:American remakes of Mexican films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Catherine Hardwicke]]\n[[Category:Films about the illegal drug trade]]\n[[Category:Films about Mexican drug cartels]]\n[[Category:Beauty pageants in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tijuana]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mexico]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 film directed by Catherine Hardwicke}}\n{{for|2019 Indian drama film|Bala (2019 film)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Miss Bala\n| image          = Miss Bala poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Catherine Hardwicke]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Pablo Cruz\n* [[Kevin Misher]]\n}}\n| writer         = Gareth Dunnett-Alcocer\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Miss Bala (2011 film)|Miss Bala]]''|Gerardo Naranjo<br>Mauricio Katz}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gina Rodriguez]]\n* [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]]\n* [[Anthony Mackie]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Alex Heffes]]\n| cinematography = Patrick Murguia\n| editing        = Terilyn A. Shropshire\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]\n* [[Canana Films]]\n* Misher Films\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|2|1|United States}}\n| runtime        = 104 minutes\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* Mexico\n}}\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* Spanish\n}}\n| budget         = $15 million<ref name=BOM/>\n| gross          = $15.4 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=missbala.htm|title=Miss Bala (2019)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=July 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NUM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Miss-Bala-(Remake)-(2019)#tab=summary|title=Miss Bala (2019)|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n'''''Miss Bala''''' (English: \"Miss Bullet\") is a 2019 [[action film|action]] [[thriller film|thriller]] film directed by [[Catherine Hardwicke]] and written by Gareth Dunnet-Alcocer, based on the [[Miss Bala (2011 film)|2011 Mexican film of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/catherine-hardwicke-miss-bala-remake-gina-rodriguez-courted-1202061089/|title=Catherine Hardwicke To Helm \u2018Miss Bala\u2019 Remake; Gina Rodriguez Courted|last=Fleming Jr|first=Mike|date=April 4, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref> The film stars [[Gina Rodriguez]], [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]], and [[Anthony Mackie]], and follows a woman who trains to take down a Mexican drug cartel after her friend is kidnapped.\n\nThe film was released in the United States on February 1, 2019, by [[Columbia Pictures]], in [[Dolby Cinema]], and grossed over $15 million on a $15 million budget making it an average grosser. While Rodriguez's performance received some praise, critics compared the film unfavorably to the original, saying it suffered from \"bland action and predictable story beats\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/miss-bala-is-a-rocky-remake/|title=Miss Bala Is A Rocky Remake|author=Ryan Fujitani|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plot== \nGloria Fuentes is a [[Latin-American]] [[makeup artist]] from [[Los Angeles]] who goes on a trip to visit her best friend Suzu in [[Tijuana, Mexico]].\n\nWhen the pair go to a local night club, Suzu plans to impress the Mexican Chief of Police, Saucedo, in order to help her chances in the Miss Baja  California beauty pageant which she has entered. When Gloria goes to the bathroom, armed gunmen break in through the vents and attempt to kidnap Gloria out of her stall but ultimately give her time to escape while they attack the club. Chaos ensues as Gloria is separated from Suzu. The next morning, Gloria is unable to get in contact with Suzu and decides to ride with a police officer to try to find Suzu. She informs the police officer that she has information on the men who attacked the club, and the officer asks her to follow him to the station. When the officer takes a break in a remote location, Gloria is taken by members of the Los Estrellas gang, the same men who shot up the club.\n\nThe gang take her to their headquarters, where Lino, the gang leader, agrees to help her find Suzu if she agrees to work for them. Gloria is reluctant but eventually agrees as she does not have much choice, and is told to get into a car and park it on a corner of a building. Gloria does the job, and when she leaves the car and joins the men at the top of a hill overlooking the building, they blow up the building, revealed to be a DEA safehouse containing three agents.\n\nLino then sends Gloria to the Miss Baja pageant, where she attempts an escape through the bathroom. Gloria escapes and encounters a DEA agent, Brian Reich, who takes her into custody and eventually lets her go but not before he puts a tracking device on her since the DEA are aiming to monitor Los Estrellas.\n\nGloria returns to Suzu's apartment and finds Lino there, and is sent to San Diego with blood money and drugs attached to her car. Upon crossing the border Gloria is given an arsenal of guns to bring back to Mexico by a gangster named Jimmy, and then told to meet in a large parking lot. Gloria then informs Brian about the meet-up at the parking lot, where he promises to send a SWAT team to rescue her during the mission to capture Lino and the Los Estrellas gang. As Gloria arrives at the parking lot, the men in Los Estrellas get their weapons. However the police show up under Brian's command, causing a gunfight to ensue in the lot. Gloria escapes to a nearby gate where Brian promised to send the SWAT team to pick her up, but sees nobody there. Gloria realizes that Brian had no intention to help her, only to capture Los Estrellas. Seeing Gloria stranded in the middle of the gunfight, Lino runs to Gloria to save her, but is shot in the leg. After a moment of hesitation, Gloria decides to help Lino and together, they escape with the other members of Los Estrellas.\n\nThe gang head to another safe house, where Gloria meets a woman named Isabella. Isabella herself was threatened into joining Los Estrellas, and bears an infigurative tattoo, meaning she belongs to them. When Gloria hears that they will be checking phones to find a mole in the group, she transfers the chip that Brian gave her to another phone. Lino brings Gloria on a ride to meet some family, and they spend time together as Lino shares his dream of living a simple life in the countryside despite his involvement in a gang. As they return to the safe house, the gang informs Lino that they have found the mole. Unknowingly and to her dismay, Gloria had put the chip in the phone belonging to Isabella, who is killed by Lino for being the suspected mole. Gloria is extremely upset, and the next morning she lashes out at Lino.\n\nLino explains his plan to kill The Mexican Chief of Police, Saucedo, to Gloria, and shows her a video of Suzu being auctioned off to various buyers. He explains that Suzu was taken the night of the club shooting, and is sold as an escort every night. His plan is to send Gloria to the Miss Baja pageant and ensure her victory by bribing the judges, afterwhich she will be invited to the afterparty organized by Saucedo. Gloria participates in the pageant and wins, and is then invited to the afterparty at Saucedo's beach home. At the party, she agrees to meet with Saucedo in one of the villas, which she informs Lino of the whereabouts via an in-ear microphone. Before meeting Saucedo, Gloria sees Suzu, and they reunite, Gloria telling Suzu that everything will be okay. However, when Suzu shows her a tattoo on her hand, the same tattoo that Isabella had, Gloria quickly realizes that Lino deceived her and that he had known where Suzu was the whole time.\n\nAs Gloria follows Saucedo into the villa, she writes on a postcard that Lino is going to kill him. Saucedo quickly escapes outside just as Los Estrellas begin their attack, and Gloria goes to find Suzu armed with a gun from one of the fallen Los Estrellas gang members. As Gloria goes to find Suzu, she is forced to shoot Saucedo in the leg after he tries to hold Suzu hostage, but then Lino kills him and thanks Gloria for her help in killing Saucedo. Gloria points her gun at Lino, confessing she knows that he was aware of Suzu's whereabouts. Lino tries to bargain with Gloria telling her that they both did what needed to be done, but she ends up shooting and killing him.\n\nThe two women are soon arrested when the cops arrive at the party, and when Gloria is taken into an interrogation room, she finds Jimmy, the man she had received the weapons from in San Diego, and realizes that he is a CIA agent. Gloria has Jimmy free Suzu and herself, and she returns Suzu to her family and goes back into the car with Jimmy, driving off to join the CIA.\n\n==Cast== \n* [[Gina Rodriguez]] as Gloria Fuentes, a [[makeup artist]] from [[Los Angeles]].\n* [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]] as Lino Esparza, the chief of Las Estrellas, a gang from [[Tijuana, Mexico|Tijuana]].\n* [[Matt Lauria]] as Brian Reich, a [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] officer.\n* [[Ricardo Abarca]] as Pollo, Lino's main henchman.\n* Cristina Rodlo as Suzu Ram\u00f3s, Gloria's best friend who lives in [[Tijuana, Mexico|Tijuana]] and a competitor on the Miss Baja California pageant.\n* Sebasti\u00e1n Cano as Chava Ram\u00f3s, Suzu's little brother who lives with her.\n* [[Dami\u00e1n Alc\u00e1zar]] as Rafael Saucedo, [[Tijuana, Mexico|Tijuana]] chief of police.\n* [[Anthony Mackie]] as Jimmy, a gangster from [[San Diego]], who is secretly a [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agent.\n* [[Aislinn Derbez]] as Isabel, a woman abducted by Las Estrellas.\n* Lilian Guadalupe Tapia Robles as Do\u00f1a Rosita, a woman who work for Las Estrellas.\n* Erick Rene Delgadillo Urbina as Tuc\u00e1n, Lino's henchman.\n* Mikhail Plata as Chivo, Lino's henchman.\n* Jorge Humberto Millan Mardue\u00f1o as Ortiz, Lino's henchman.\n* [[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]] as Justin, Gloria's boss in [[Los Angeles]].\n* Jos\u00e9 Sefami as Don Ramon, a man who work for Rafael Saucedo.\n* Gaby Orihuela as the coordinator of the Miss Baja California pageant.\n* Roberto Sosa as the police officer who secretly work for Las Estrellas.\n\n==Production==\nIn April 2017, it was announced [[Catherine Hardwicke]] would direct the film, from a screenplay by Gareth Dunnet-Alcocer, with [[Kevin Misher]] and Pablo Cruz producing the film, with [[Andy Berman]] serving as an executive producer on the film. In May 2017, [[Gina Rodriguez]] and [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/gina-rodriguez-ismael-cruz-cordova-miss-bala-sony-1202092067/|title=Gina Rodriguez Set To Star In \u2018Miss Bala\u2019, Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova Cast As Male Lead|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=May 15, 2017|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref> In July 2017, [[Matt Lauria]], Cristina Rodlo, and [[Aislinn Derbez]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/matt-lauria-cristina-rodlo-gina-rodriguez-in-miss-bala-remake-1202500248/|title=Matt Lauria and Cristina Rodlo Join Gina Rodriguez in \u2018Miss Bala\u2019 Remake (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=July 19, 2017|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BWi_ZUggtFR/|title=Hot set with these crazy people @hereisgina @ismaelcruzcordova @richieabarca #moviemaking \ud83d\ude0d\ud83c\udfac\ud83c\udfa5|website=[[Instagram]]|first=Aislinn|last=Derbez|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref> [[Anthony Mackie]] later joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/miss-bala-animated-spider-man-show-sonys-commitment-to-diverse-heroes-1202784274/|title=\u2018Miss Bala,\u2019 Animated Spider-Man Show Sony\u2019s Commitment to Diverse Heroes|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=April 23, 2018|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref> The cast and crew are said to be 95 percent [[Latino]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cinemacon-sony-touts-diversity-upcoming-movies-1105236|title=CinemaCon: Sony Touts Diversity of Its Upcoming Movies|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Lopez 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/miss-bala-gina-rodriguez-1203029195/|title=Gina Rodriguez\u2019s \u2018Miss Bala\u2019 Features Rare Leading Role for Latinx Actor, Diverse Crew|last=Lopez|first=Ricardo|date=2018-11-16|work=Variety|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en-US}}</ref> Sony reportedly spent $15 million producing the film.<ref name=\"Lopez 2018\" />\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released in the United States on February 1, 2019, after having previously been set for a January 25, 2019 release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/sony-dates-trio-for-2019-miss-bala-a-dogs-way-home-the-crow-1202308464/|title=Sony Dates Trio For 2019: \u2018Miss Bala\u2019, \u2018A Dog\u2019s Way Home\u2019 & \u2018The Crow\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=March 2, 2018|accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/escape-room-miss-bala-release-date-sony-gina-rodriguez-tyler-labine-1202482018/|title=Sony Moves \u2018Escape Room\u2019 Up By A Month & \u2018Miss Bala\u2019 By A Week|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Erik|last=Pederson|date=October 12, 2018|accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref> It was in the United Kingdom on February 8, 2019.<ref name=\"Filmoria\">{{cite web|url=https://www.filmoria.co.uk/presenting-the-first-trailer-poster-and-images-for-miss-bala/|title=Miss Bala - The First Trailer, Poster and Images|publisher=Filmoria.co.uk |access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Miss Bala'' has grossed $15 million in the United States and Canada, and $173,237 in other territories, for a worldwide gross of $15.2 million, against a production budget of $15 million.<ref name=BOM/><ref name=NUM/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Miss Bala'' was projected to gross $6\u20139 million from 2,203 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=preview>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-box-office-miss-bala-glass-20190130-story.html|title=Can Gina Rodriguez's action movie 'Miss Bala' unseat 'Glass' at the box office?|work=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |date=January 30, 2019 |first=Ryan |last=Faughnder|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> It made $2.8 million on its first day, including $650,000 from Thursday night previews. It went on to debut to $6.7 million, finishing third at the box office. ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' wrote that given its $15 million production budget, an opening of $10\u201312 million would've been an ideal start in order for the film to turn a profit.<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/miss-bala-fires-up-650k-in-previews-before-heading-into-slow-super-bowl-weekend-1202547407/|title=\u2018Glass\u2019 Still Has Class With Third Weekend Win; \u2018Miss Bala\u2019 Fires Blanks In Lowest Super Bowl Frame In 19 Years \u2013 Sunday Final|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 3, 2018|first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> It fell 60% in its second weekend to $2.7 million, finishing 10th.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/lego-movie-2-chris-pratt-what-men-want-cold-pursuit-liam-neeson-box-office-weekend-1202552562/|title=\u2018Lego Movie 2\u2019 Comes Apart With $34M+ Opening; \u2018What Men Want\u2019 Solid With $18M+ In Another Blas\u00e9 B.O. Weekend|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 10, 2018|first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 22% based on 105 reviews, with an average rating of 4.59/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Miss Bala'' suggests Gina Rodriguez has a future as an action hero; unfortunately, it also demonstrates how hard it is to balance set pieces against a compelling story.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/miss_bala_2019|title=Miss Bala (2019)|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[weighted average]] score of 41 out of 100, based on 30 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/miss-bala-2019|title=Miss Bala reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 3.5 out of 5 stars; social media monitor RelishMix noted online responses to the film were \"mixed-to-negative\".<ref name=opening/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemascore.com|title=Find CinemaScore|format=Type \"Miss Bala\" in the search box|publisher=[[CinemaScore]]|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Roeper]], writing for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' was critical of the film, saying, \"Run away from Gina Rodriguez's ludicrous drug running shoot-em-up... ''Miss Bala'' is an early contender for a spot on my list of the worst movies of 2019.\"<ref name=opening/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDB title|5941692}}\n* {{Mojo title|missbala}}\n\n{{Catherine Hardwicke}}\n\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American crime drama films]]\n[[Category:Mexican films]]\n[[Category:Mexican action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Mexican crime drama films]]\n[[Category:American remakes of Mexican films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Catherine Hardwicke]]\n[[Category:Films about the illegal drug trade]]\n[[Category:Films about Mexican drug cartels]]\n[[Category:Beauty pageants in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tijuana]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mexico]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLatino(link changed toHispanic and Latino Americans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miss_Bala_(2019_film)"}
{"title_page": "Alicia Cuar\u00f3n", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| pre-nominals = Sister\n| name          = Alicia Valladolid Cuar\u00f3n\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1939|03|01}}\n| birth_place   = [[Oxnard, California]], US\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = 1972\u2013present\n| known_for     = Education and leadership development for low-income [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latinas]] and Spanish-speaking immigrant families\n| notable_works = \n| awards        = [[Colorado Women's Hall of Fame]], 2008\n}}\nSister '''Alicia Valladolid Cuar\u00f3n''' (born March 1, 1939) is a [[Mexican Americans|Mexican-American]] educator, [[Human rights activists|human rights activist]], [[women's rights]] activist, [[leadership development]] specialist, and [[Franciscans|Franciscan]] [[nun]]. Since the 1970s, she has crafted numerous initiatives benefiting low-income [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latinas]] and Spanish-speaking immigrant families in [[Colorado]], including the first bilingual and bicultural [[Head Start (program)|Head Start]] program in the state, the national [[Adelante Mujer]] Hispanic Employment and Training Conference, and the Bienestar Family Services Center, today a ministry of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archdiocese of Denver]]. In 1992, Cuar\u00f3n joined the [[Sisters of St. Francis of Penance and Christian Charity]], where she continues her efforts to promote education and leadership development among Spanish-speaking families. She was inducted into the [[Colorado Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2008.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAlicia Valladolid Cuar\u00f3n was born on March 1, 1939, in [[Oxnard, California]].{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}} Her parents, Rosenado Alfaro and Guadalupe Valladolid (Perez) Cuar\u00f3n, had immigrated to the United States from Mexico during the [[Mexican Revolution]] of 1910\u20131920.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}} Her father was one of the \"[[Cristero War|Cristeros]]\" (followers of [[Jesus Christ|Christ]]) who helped smuggle Catholic priests and nuns across the Mexican border into the United States in the 1920s.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}} She has five sisters and a brother.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}}\n\nAt the age of 3 she moved with her family to [[El Paso, Texas]].{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}} She went on to attend the [[University of Texas at El Paso]], working in the university library to pay for her studies, and graduated with a B.A. in education in 1961.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} She is fluent in both English and Spanish.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}\n\n==Career==\nCuar\u00f3n began teaching remedial reading and [[English as a second or foreign language|English as a second language]] in the first-grade [[Special education in the United States|special education program]] at Navarro Elementary School in El Paso. At the time, the student body was 90-percent Spanish-speaking and from poor families.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} She also taught in the [[Head Start (program)|Head Start]] program and in [[adult education]] classes.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}\n\nCuar\u00f3n moved to [[Colorado]] in the early 1970s. She earned her M.A. in education in 1972 at the [[University of Northern Colorado]] in [[Greeley, Colorado|Greeley]], and her Ph.D. at the same institution in 1975.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} While studying for her degrees, she instituted a bilingual and bicultural Head Start program in [[Denver]], a first for the state.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} She later developed a bilingual and multicultural Child Development Associate Head Start program at the [[Metropolitan State University of Denver|Metropolitan State College]] of Denver,{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} where she was an assistant professor of education from 1974 to 1980.\n\nIn the 1970s and 1980s she conducted leadership training seminars for Latinas throughout the United States as founding director of EXITO (Institute for Hispanic Professional Development).<ref name=trail>{{cite web |url=https://latinasfirstfoundation.org/profile/sister-alicia-cuaron-ed-d-trailblazer-2013/|title=Sister Alicia Cuaron, Ed.D., Trailblazer 2013|publisher=Latinas First Foundation|year=2018|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=ecc>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21106755/the_daily_herald/|title='Latina Agenda: 2000 and Beyond' set at ECC|work=The Daily Herald|date=March 16, 2000|accessdate=June 20, 2018|page=V3|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> In 1980 she co-founded the national [[Adelante Mujer]] Hispanic Employment and Training Conference, which attracted 1,000 women to discussions on education and career training.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}{{sfn|United States Women's Bureau|1980}}\n\nCuar\u00f3n began working in the management consultancy field in the 1980s. She headed two consultancy companies, and also served as executive vice-president of Source One, an operations and facilities management firm.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}\n\n==Keynote speaker==\nCuar\u00f3n was a popular [[keynote]] speaker for conferences run by corporations, charities, community colleges and universities. Her motivational talks for Latina audiences stressed education and leadership development, and she shared her own challenges and successes as a minority woman in the business world.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}}<ref name=hall/> She is one of the first Latinas invited to speak at [[Yale University|Yale]], [[Stanford University|Stanford]], [[University of California, Berkeley|Berkeley]], and [[Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study]] at [[Harvard University]].{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}}\n\n==Franciscan nun==\nIn 1992, Cuar\u00f3n left her business career to join the [[Sisters of St. Francis of Penance and Christian Charity]] in Denver.<ref name=post>{{cite web |url= https://www.denverpost.com/2014/06/06/sister-alicia-cuaron-75-leaves-bienestar-family-services-in-denver/|title= Sister Alicia Cuaron, 75, leaves Bienestar Family Services in Denver|first=Colleen|last=O'Connor|date=June 6, 2014|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=[[The Denver Post]]}}</ref><ref name=encore>{{cite web |url=https://encore.org/purpose-prize/alicia-cuaron/|title=Alicia Cuaron|publisher=encore.org|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref> She took her vows as a Marycrest Franciscan Sister four years later.<ref name=joanne/> Posted in a parish with many immigrant, low-income residents, she continued her efforts to promote education and leadership development.<ref name=encore/> She was the founding director of the Familia Franciscan AIDS Ministry,<ref name=hall/> and in 1998 established the Bienestar Family Services Center in the former [[Saint Joseph High School (Denver, Colorado)|St Joseph High School]] to provide adult education, career training, and support services for new immigrant families.<ref name=encore/><ref name=thank/> In 2004, Cuar\u00f3n moved the Bienestar Family Center to Centro San Juan Diego, the Hispanic ministry of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archdiocese of Denver]]. Cuar\u00f3n served as director of Bienestar from 2004 to 2014.<ref name=post/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://denvercatholic.org/bienestar-family-services-founder-announces-retirement/|title= Bienestar Family Services founder announces retirement|first=Roxanne|last=King|date=June 3, 2014|accessdate=June 20, 2018|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archdiocese of Denver]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 Cuar\u00f3n co-founded the Latina SafeHouse to support victims of domestic violence in Denver with \"culturally and linguistically responsive behavioral health counseling, self-sufficiency, advocacy, and legal services\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lavozcolorado.com/detail.php?id=9380|title=A look at domestic violence in Colorado|first=Joseph|last=Rios|date=October 25, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=La Voz Colorado}}</ref> She launched the SafeHouse's annual \"Vino y Chocolate\" social event to which attendees bring wrapped gifts to be distributed to needy children at Christmas.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://lavozcolorado.com/detail.php?id=9434|title='Vino y Chocolate helps bring in the Christmas season'|first=Joseph|last=Rios|date=November 29, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=La Voz Colorado}}</ref> Cuar\u00f3n also initiated the FaithAction task force for the preservation of religious landmarks in Denver; the initiative is now part of Historic Denver.<ref name=hall/>{{sfn|Catlett|2007|p=40}}\n\n==Memberships and affiliations==\nIn 1980 Cuar\u00f3n was named executive director of the Colorado Economic Development Association in Denver, becoming the first Latina to fill that role.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}<ref name=hall/> She was also the first Latina to serve as [[Colorado State Fair]] Commissioner, and the first woman appointed executive director of the National Hispanic Association of Construction Enterprises.<ref name=trail/><ref name=hall/> She has served as chair of the Colorado Council on Working Women<ref name=trail/><ref name=hall/> and national director of leadership, education, and educational development for the [[League of United Latin American Citizens]].<ref name=ecc/> She is a co-founder of the Circle of Latina Leadership.<ref name=hall/>\n\nCuar\u00f3n is an executive board member of the Colorado\u2019s Women\u2019s Forum. She has also served on the [[Colorado Supreme Court]] Nominating Committee.<ref name=trail/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nCuar\u00f3n has received accolades from numerous groups, including the [[American Jewish Committee]], Big Sisters of Colorado, Chicana Service Center, and Denver [[Federal Executive Boards|Federal Executive Board]].{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} In 2000 she received the Maclovio Barraza Award for Leadership from the [[UnidosUS|National Council of La Raza]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conferencenclrorg.businesscatalyst.com/past-honorees.html|title=Conference Past Awardees|publisher=[[UnidosUS]]|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref> In 2008 she was the recipient of the Colorado Women\u2019s Chamber of Commerce ATHENA Award, and in 2009 the Colorado Rockies Community Award.<ref name=thank>{{cite web |url=https://archden.org/archbishop-thankful-gift-sister-alicia/#.WyqXZ6czY00|title=Archbishop thankful for the 'gift of Sister Alicia' (press release)|first=Jennie |last=Marquez|date=June 6, 2014|accessdate=June 20, 2018|publisher=Archdiocese of Denver}}</ref> Cuar\u00f3n was honored as \"Woman of the Year\" by the Colorado Hispanic Chamber of Commerce, and named one of the \"100 Most Influential Hispanics in America\" by ''Hispanic Business'' magazine.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} She was inducted into the [[Colorado Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2008.<ref name=hall>{{cite web|url=http://www.cogreatwomen.org/project/alicia-valladolid-Cuar\u00f3n/|title=Sister Alicia Cuar\u00f3n, EDD|year=2018|accessdate=June 20, 2018|publisher=[[Colorado Women's Hall of Fame]]}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCuar\u00f3n has one daughter, Alexis Maritza Cuar\u00f3n-Anderten.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}<ref name=joanne>{{cite web |url= http://extras.denverpost.com/scene/jd1203.htm|title=Reception fetes Adelante Mujer|first=Joanne|last=Davidson|date=December 3, 2000|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=The Denver Post}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tq-lga6iFbEC&pg=PA40 |title=Farmlands, Forts, and Country Life: The Story of Southwest Denver|first=Sharon R.|last=Catlett|year=2007|publisher=Big Earth Publishing|isbn= 1565795458}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=dCWqXOE5lmgC&pg=PA118 |title=Notable Hispanic American Women|volume=1|editor-first=Diane|editor-last=Telgen|year=1993|publisher=VNR AG|isbn=0810375788}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|United States Women's Bureau}}|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qZlAAAAAYAAJ&q=Alicia+Cuar%C3%B3n |title=Adelante, Mujer Hispana: A Conference Model for Hispanic Women|publisher=[[United States Women's Bureau]]|year=1980}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xYwLAAAAYAAJ&q=Alicia+Cuar%C3%B3n&dq=Alicia+Cuar%C3%B3n&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJw9273ODbAhXC_SwKHRzIDvMQ6AEIRjAH|chapter=Chapter 21: Alicia Cuaron|title=Breaking Ground and Barriers: Hispanic Women Developing Effective Leadership|editor-first=Gloria|editor-last=Bonille|year=1992|publisher=Marin Publications|isbn=0927065088}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0t7-gF8tDHE \"Colorado Makers: Alicia Cuar\u00f3n\"] Rocky Mountain PBS, October 30, 2014\n\n{{Colorado Women's Hall of Fame|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuar\u00f3n, Alicia}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women educators]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic religious sisters and nuns]]\n[[Category:American human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Activists from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Franciscan nuns]]\n[[Category:American people of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at El Paso alumni]]\n[[Category:People from El Paso, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Denver]]\n[[Category:People from Oxnard, California]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Texas]]\n[[Category:Catholics from California]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Educators from Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| pre-nominals = Sister\n| name          = Alicia Valladolid Cuar\u00f3n\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1939|03|01}}\n| birth_place   = [[Oxnard, California]], US\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = 1972\u2013present\n| known_for     = Education and leadership development for low-income [[Latino|Latinas]] and Spanish-speaking immigrant families\n| notable_works = \n| awards        = [[Colorado Women's Hall of Fame]], 2008\n}}\nSister '''Alicia Valladolid Cuar\u00f3n''' (born March 1, 1939) is a [[Mexican Americans|Mexican-American]] educator, [[Human rights activists|human rights activist]], [[women's rights]] activist, [[leadership development]] specialist, and [[Franciscans|Franciscan]] [[nun]]. Since the 1970s, she has crafted numerous initiatives benefiting low-income [[Latino|Latinas]] and Spanish-speaking immigrant families in [[Colorado]], including the first bilingual and bicultural [[Head Start (program)|Head Start]] program in the state, the national [[Adelante Mujer]] Hispanic Employment and Training Conference, and the Bienestar Family Services Center, today a ministry of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archdiocese of Denver]]. In 1992, Cuar\u00f3n joined the [[Sisters of St. Francis of Penance and Christian Charity]], where she continues her efforts to promote education and leadership development among Spanish-speaking families. She was inducted into the [[Colorado Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2008.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAlicia Valladolid Cuar\u00f3n was born on March 1, 1939, in [[Oxnard, California]].{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}} Her parents, Rosenado Alfaro and Guadalupe Valladolid (Perez) Cuar\u00f3n, had immigrated to the United States from Mexico during the [[Mexican Revolution]] of 1910\u20131920.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}} Her father was one of the \"[[Cristero War|Cristeros]]\" (followers of [[Jesus Christ|Christ]]) who helped smuggle Catholic priests and nuns across the Mexican border into the United States in the 1920s.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}} She has five sisters and a brother.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}}\n\nAt the age of 3 she moved with her family to [[El Paso, Texas]].{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}} She went on to attend the [[University of Texas at El Paso]], working in the university library to pay for her studies, and graduated with a B.A. in education in 1961.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} She is fluent in both English and Spanish.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}\n\n==Career==\nCuar\u00f3n began teaching remedial reading and [[English as a second or foreign language|English as a second language]] in the first-grade [[Special education in the United States|special education program]] at Navarro Elementary School in El Paso. At the time, the student body was 90-percent Spanish-speaking and from poor families.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} She also taught in the [[Head Start (program)|Head Start]] program and in [[adult education]] classes.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}\n\nCuar\u00f3n moved to [[Colorado]] in the early 1970s. She earned her M.A. in education in 1972 at the [[University of Northern Colorado]] in [[Greeley, Colorado|Greeley]], and her Ph.D. at the same institution in 1975.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} While studying for her degrees, she instituted a bilingual and bicultural Head Start program in [[Denver]], a first for the state.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} She later developed a bilingual and multicultural Child Development Associate Head Start program at the [[Metropolitan State University of Denver|Metropolitan State College]] of Denver,{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} where she was an assistant professor of education from 1974 to 1980.\n\nIn the 1970s and 1980s she conducted leadership training seminars for Latinas throughout the United States as founding director of EXITO (Institute for Hispanic Professional Development).<ref name=trail>{{cite web |url=https://latinasfirstfoundation.org/profile/sister-alicia-cuaron-ed-d-trailblazer-2013/|title=Sister Alicia Cuaron, Ed.D., Trailblazer 2013|publisher=Latinas First Foundation|year=2018|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=ecc>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21106755/the_daily_herald/|title='Latina Agenda: 2000 and Beyond' set at ECC|work=The Daily Herald|date=March 16, 2000|accessdate=June 20, 2018|page=V3|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> In 1980 she co-founded the national [[Adelante Mujer]] Hispanic Employment and Training Conference, which attracted 1,000 women to discussions on education and career training.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}{{sfn|United States Women's Bureau|1980}}\n\nCuar\u00f3n began working in the management consultancy field in the 1980s. She headed two consultancy companies, and also served as executive vice-president of Source One, an operations and facilities management firm.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}\n\n==Keynote speaker==\nCuar\u00f3n was a popular [[keynote]] speaker for conferences run by corporations, charities, community colleges and universities. Her motivational talks for Latina audiences stressed education and leadership development, and she shared her own challenges and successes as a minority woman in the business world.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}}<ref name=hall/> She is one of the first Latinas invited to speak at [[Yale University|Yale]], [[Stanford University|Stanford]], [[University of California, Berkeley|Berkeley]], and [[Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study]] at [[Harvard University]].{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=118}}\n\n==Franciscan nun==\nIn 1992, Cuar\u00f3n left her business career to join the [[Sisters of St. Francis of Penance and Christian Charity]] in Denver.<ref name=post>{{cite web |url= https://www.denverpost.com/2014/06/06/sister-alicia-cuaron-75-leaves-bienestar-family-services-in-denver/|title= Sister Alicia Cuaron, 75, leaves Bienestar Family Services in Denver|first=Colleen|last=O'Connor|date=June 6, 2014|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=[[The Denver Post]]}}</ref><ref name=encore>{{cite web |url=https://encore.org/purpose-prize/alicia-cuaron/|title=Alicia Cuaron|publisher=encore.org|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref> She took her vows as a Marycrest Franciscan Sister four years later.<ref name=joanne/> Posted in a parish with many immigrant, low-income residents, she continued her efforts to promote education and leadership development.<ref name=encore/> She was the founding director of the Familia Franciscan AIDS Ministry,<ref name=hall/> and in 1998 established the Bienestar Family Services Center in the former [[Saint Joseph High School (Denver, Colorado)|St Joseph High School]] to provide adult education, career training, and support services for new immigrant families.<ref name=encore/><ref name=thank/> In 2004, Cuar\u00f3n moved the Bienestar Family Center to Centro San Juan Diego, the Hispanic ministry of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archdiocese of Denver]]. Cuar\u00f3n served as director of Bienestar from 2004 to 2014.<ref name=post/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://denvercatholic.org/bienestar-family-services-founder-announces-retirement/|title= Bienestar Family Services founder announces retirement|first=Roxanne|last=King|date=June 3, 2014|accessdate=June 20, 2018|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archdiocese of Denver]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 Cuar\u00f3n co-founded the Latina SafeHouse to support victims of domestic violence in Denver with \"culturally and linguistically responsive behavioral health counseling, self-sufficiency, advocacy, and legal services\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lavozcolorado.com/detail.php?id=9380|title=A look at domestic violence in Colorado|first=Joseph|last=Rios|date=October 25, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=La Voz Colorado}}</ref> She launched the SafeHouse's annual \"Vino y Chocolate\" social event to which attendees bring wrapped gifts to be distributed to needy children at Christmas.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://lavozcolorado.com/detail.php?id=9434|title='Vino y Chocolate helps bring in the Christmas season'|first=Joseph|last=Rios|date=November 29, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=La Voz Colorado}}</ref> Cuar\u00f3n also initiated the FaithAction task force for the preservation of religious landmarks in Denver; the initiative is now part of Historic Denver.<ref name=hall/>{{sfn|Catlett|2007|p=40}}\n\n==Memberships and affiliations==\nIn 1980 Cuar\u00f3n was named executive director of the Colorado Economic Development Association in Denver, becoming the first Latina to fill that role.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}<ref name=hall/> She was also the first Latina to serve as [[Colorado State Fair]] Commissioner, and the first woman appointed executive director of the National Hispanic Association of Construction Enterprises.<ref name=trail/><ref name=hall/> She has served as chair of the Colorado Council on Working Women<ref name=trail/><ref name=hall/> and national director of leadership, education, and educational development for the [[League of United Latin American Citizens]].<ref name=ecc/> She is a co-founder of the Circle of Latina Leadership.<ref name=hall/>\n\nCuar\u00f3n is an executive board member of the Colorado\u2019s Women\u2019s Forum. She has also served on the [[Colorado Supreme Court]] Nominating Committee.<ref name=trail/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nCuar\u00f3n has received accolades from numerous groups, including the [[American Jewish Committee]], Big Sisters of Colorado, Chicana Service Center, and Denver [[Federal Executive Boards|Federal Executive Board]].{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} In 2000 she received the Maclovio Barraza Award for Leadership from the [[UnidosUS|National Council of La Raza]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conferencenclrorg.businesscatalyst.com/past-honorees.html|title=Conference Past Awardees|publisher=[[UnidosUS]]|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref> In 2008 she was the recipient of the Colorado Women\u2019s Chamber of Commerce ATHENA Award, and in 2009 the Colorado Rockies Community Award.<ref name=thank>{{cite web |url=https://archden.org/archbishop-thankful-gift-sister-alicia/#.WyqXZ6czY00|title=Archbishop thankful for the 'gift of Sister Alicia' (press release)|first=Jennie |last=Marquez|date=June 6, 2014|accessdate=June 20, 2018|publisher=Archdiocese of Denver}}</ref> Cuar\u00f3n was honored as \"Woman of the Year\" by the Colorado Hispanic Chamber of Commerce, and named one of the \"100 Most Influential Hispanics in America\" by ''Hispanic Business'' magazine.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}} She was inducted into the [[Colorado Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2008.<ref name=hall>{{cite web|url=http://www.cogreatwomen.org/project/alicia-valladolid-Cuar\u00f3n/|title=Sister Alicia Cuar\u00f3n, EDD|year=2018|accessdate=June 20, 2018|publisher=[[Colorado Women's Hall of Fame]]}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCuar\u00f3n has one daughter, Alexis Maritza Cuar\u00f3n-Anderten.{{sfn|Telgen|1993|p=119}}<ref name=joanne>{{cite web |url= http://extras.denverpost.com/scene/jd1203.htm|title=Reception fetes Adelante Mujer|first=Joanne|last=Davidson|date=December 3, 2000|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=The Denver Post}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tq-lga6iFbEC&pg=PA40 |title=Farmlands, Forts, and Country Life: The Story of Southwest Denver|first=Sharon R.|last=Catlett|year=2007|publisher=Big Earth Publishing|isbn= 1565795458}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=dCWqXOE5lmgC&pg=PA118 |title=Notable Hispanic American Women|volume=1|editor-first=Diane|editor-last=Telgen|year=1993|publisher=VNR AG|isbn=0810375788}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|United States Women's Bureau}}|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qZlAAAAAYAAJ&q=Alicia+Cuar%C3%B3n |title=Adelante, Mujer Hispana: A Conference Model for Hispanic Women|publisher=[[United States Women's Bureau]]|year=1980}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xYwLAAAAYAAJ&q=Alicia+Cuar%C3%B3n&dq=Alicia+Cuar%C3%B3n&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJw9273ODbAhXC_SwKHRzIDvMQ6AEIRjAH|chapter=Chapter 21: Alicia Cuaron|title=Breaking Ground and Barriers: Hispanic Women Developing Effective Leadership|editor-first=Gloria|editor-last=Bonille|year=1992|publisher=Marin Publications|isbn=0927065088}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0t7-gF8tDHE \"Colorado Makers: Alicia Cuar\u00f3n\"] Rocky Mountain PBS, October 30, 2014\n\n{{Colorado Women's Hall of Fame|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuar\u00f3n, Alicia}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women educators]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic religious sisters and nuns]]\n[[Category:American human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Activists from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Franciscan nuns]]\n[[Category:American people of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at El Paso alumni]]\n[[Category:People from El Paso, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Denver]]\n[[Category:People from Oxnard, California]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Texas]]\n[[Category:Catholics from California]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Educators from Texas]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLatino(link changed toHispanic and Latino Americans; link changed toHispanic and Latino Americans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alicia_Cuar%C3%B3n"}
